Truth-Constrained Language Models: A Control-Theoretic and Optimization Framework for Eliminating Strategic Misalignment

ouadi Maakoul 

April 2026

---

Abstract

Large Language Models (LLMs) optimize objectives that often trade factual accuracy for fluency or helpfulness, yielding systematic hallucination under incentive misalignment. This thesis formalizes truthfulness as a hard constraint within a unified optimization and control framework. We develop a constrained alignment methodology based on primal-dual Direct Preference Optimization (PD-DPO) that solves a truth-constrained objective with rigorous suboptimality and constraint-violation bounds under Slater's condition and the Bradley-Terry preference model. At inference, we treat autoregressive token generation as a discrete dynamical system and enforce forward invariance of a truthfulness safe set via a discrete Control Barrier Function (CBF) safety filter. The filter acts as a minimal-intervention projection on the token distribution, guaranteeing that every generated trajectory remains within a prescribed truthfulness threshold. We establish complete theoretical guarantees for saddle-point convergence, discrete-time forward invariance, robustness to bounded verifier error, and compositional safety under multiple constraints. The framework elevates truth from a soft preference to a provably invariant dynamical property, providing a mathematically rigorous foundation for reliable language generation without reliance on empirical heuristics.

---

Chapter 1: Introduction

1.1 Motivation and Problem Statement

Autoregressive language models generate sequences by maximizing a learned objective that aggregates multiple behavioral preferences: helpfulness, coherence, instruction adherence, and stylistic alignment. When these objectives conflict with factual accuracy, gradient-based optimization naturally exploits the reward landscape, producing fluent but incorrect outputs. This phenomenon, known as strategic misalignment, arises from the absence of hard constraints on truthfulness in standard alignment formulations.

Current approaches to improving factual reliability fall into two broad categories. Post-hoc verification methods check generated text against external knowledge bases but cannot prevent hallucination at the generation source. Reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) and direct preference optimization (DPO) incorporate truthfulness as a soft reward component, which the model may trade off against other objectives. Neither approach provides formal guarantees that generated text will satisfy a minimum truthfulness threshold.

This thesis addresses strategic misalignment through a mathematically rigorous framework that enforces truthfulness as a constraint rather than a penalty. We formalize the alignment problem as a constrained optimization over policy space, derive a primal-dual training algorithm with provable convergence guarantees, and construct a discrete-time control-theoretic safety layer that guarantees forward invariance of a truth-safe set during autoregressive generation. The framework is purely theoretical: all claims are supported by definitions, assumptions, theorems, and proofs. Empirical validation is explicitly deferred to future work; the present contribution lies in the formal synthesis of constrained preference optimization and discrete control barrier functions for language model safety.

1.2 Contributions

This thesis makes the following theoretical contributions:

1. Formalization of Truth-Constrained Alignment: We formulate a constrained optimization problem over policy space with a hard truthfulness threshold. Using Lagrangian duality and Slater's condition, we establish strong duality and characterize the optimal policy structure under the Bradley-Terry preference model.
2. Primal-Dual DPO Theory: We derive a Lagrangian DPO objective that eliminates the reward partition function via a pre-trained reward-aligned policy. We prove convergence of primal-dual updates at rate $\mathcal{O}(1/\sqrt{K})$ and establish explicit bounds on suboptimality and constraint violation.
3. Discrete CBF Safety Filter: We model autoregressive generation as a discrete dynamical system and construct a token-level safety filter that guarantees forward invariance of a truth-safe set. We prove recursive feasibility conditions and characterize the filter as a minimal KL-divergence projection.
4. End-to-End Robust Guarantees: We prove that bounded verifier error translates to bounded truthfulness degradation, and we extend the framework to multiple constraints via compositional CBF theory.
5. Complete Theoretical Analysis: We provide a unified treatment of saddle-point convergence, discrete-time stability, and approximation-theoretic bounds, establishing a self-contained mathematical foundation for truth-constrained language generation.

1.3 Thesis Organization

Chapter 2 establishes mathematical preliminaries covering probability spaces, policy representations, preference models, convex duality, and control barrier functions. Chapter 3 formalizes the truth-constrained alignment problem and its Lagrangian reformulation. Chapter 4 develops the primal-dual DPO algorithm with convergence guarantees. Chapter 5 introduces discrete CBF filtering for autoregressive generation and proves forward invariance. Chapter 6 integrates the training and inference components and establishes end-to-end truthfulness guarantees. Chapter 7 analyzes verifier approximation error and robust invariance. Chapter 8 provides unified convergence and stability analysis. Chapter 9 discusses theoretical limitations and open problems. Chapter 10 concludes.

