Chapter 6: Integrated Framework and End-to-End Guarantees

6.1 Composition of Training and Inference

The complete framework consists of two stages:

1. Training: Apply Primal-Dual DPO to obtain a policy $\pi_{\text{tc}}$ that approximately satisfies $J_T(\pi_{\text{tc}}) \geq \tau$.
2. Inference: During autoregressive generation, apply the CBF safety filter to enforce per-step truthfulness $V(s_k) \geq \tau$.

We now prove that this combination provides end-to-end guarantees.

6.2 End-to-End Truthfulness Guarantee

Theorem 6.2.1 (End-to-End Truth Guarantee). Assume:

1. PD-DPO yields a policy $\pi_{\text{tc}}$ with expected constraint violation $\delta_K = \mathbb{E}[(\tau - J_T(\pi_{\text{tc}}))_+] \leq \delta$.
2. The verifier $V$ has uniform approximation error bounded by $\epsilon$: $\sup_{x,y} |V(x,y) - T(x,y)| \leq \epsilon$.
3. The CBF filter is applied with threshold $\tau$ and enforces $V(x, s_k) \geq \tau$ for all $k$.

Then for any prompt $x$, the generated sequence $y = s_L$ satisfies:

T(x, y) \geq \tau - \epsilon

Proof. From the CBF forward invariance (Theorem 5.5.1), $V(x, y) \geq \tau$. By the verifier error bound, $T(x, y) \geq V(x, y) - |V(x, y) - T(x, y)| \geq \tau - \epsilon$. $\square$

Remark 6.2.1. This guarantee is per-sample and holds deterministically for the generated sequence, assuming the CBF filter always finds a safe token (Assumption 5.3.1). The training-time expected constraint violation $\delta_K$ does not affect the per-sample inference guarantee but improves the quality of the nominal policy $\pi_{\text{tc}}$, making it more likely to generate safe tokens naturally and reducing the intervention frequency of the filter.

6.3 Quality Preservation Bound

The CBF filter modifies the token distribution; we bound the resulting degradation in expected reward.

Theorem 6.3.1 (Reward Degradation). Let $Q(\cdot \mid x, s)$ be the safe distribution and $P(\cdot \mid x, s)$ the nominal distribution from $\pi_{\text{tc}}$. The expected reduction in reward per step due to the filter is bounded by:

\mathbb{E}_{u \sim P}[R] - \mathbb{E}_{u \sim Q}[R] \leq \|R\|_\infty \cdot D_{\text{KL}}(Q \parallel P)^{1/2} \cdot \sqrt{2}

by Pinsker's inequality. Moreover, if the nominal policy already satisfies the constraint with high probability, the KL divergence is small.

Proof. The difference in expectations is bounded by the total variation distance: $|\mathbb{E}_P[R] - \mathbb{E}_Q[R]| \leq \|R\|_\infty \cdot \|P - Q\|_1$. By Pinsker's inequality, $\|P - Q\|_1 \leq \sqrt{2 D_{\text{KL}}(Q \parallel P)}$. The KL divergence is the minimal among all safe distributions. $\square$

6.4 Compositional Safety with Multiple Constraints

The CBF framework extends naturally to multiple constraints.

Definition 6.4.1 (Multiple Barrier Functions). Let $h_1, \dots, h_m: \mathcal{Y} \to \mathbb{R}$ be barrier functions for constraints $\mathcal{C}_i = \{s : h_i(s) \geq 0\}$. Define the intersection safe set $\mathcal{C} = \bigcap_{i=1}^m \mathcal{C}_i$.

Theorem 6.4.1 (Compositional Forward Invariance). Suppose each $h_i$ is a discrete CBF with parameter $\gamma_i \in [0,1)$. If at each step the control $u$ is chosen such that $h_i(s \oplus u) \geq \gamma_i h_i(s)$ for all $i$, then the system is forward invariant with respect to $\mathcal{C}$.

Proof. By component-wise induction: $h_i(s_0) \geq 0$ for all $i$. Assuming $h_i(s_k) \geq 0$, the condition ensures $h_i(s_{k+1}) \geq \gamma_i h_i(s_k) \geq 0$. Thus $s_{k+1} \in \mathcal{C}_i$ for all $i$, so $s_{k+1} \in \bigcap_i \mathcal{C}_i = \mathcal{C}$. $\square$

Corollary 6.4.1 (Multi-Constraint Safety Filter). The KL-projection problem with multiple constraints is:

\min_{Q} D_{\text{KL}}(Q \parallel P) \quad \text{s.t.} \quad \mathbb{E}_Q[h_i(s \oplus u)] \geq \gamma_i h_i(s), \; i=1,\dots,m

The solution has the form $Q(u) \propto P(u) \exp(\sum_{i=1}^m \mu_i h_i(s \oplus u))$ with $\mu_i \geq 0$.

