Chapter 7: Verifier Approximation Theory and Robust Invariance

7.1 Approximation Framework

In practice, the ground-truth truthfulness $T(x,y)$ is unknown, and we must rely on a learned verifier $V(x,y)$.

Definition 7.1.1 (Verifier Approximation Error). Let $\mathcal{F}$ be a class of measurable functions from $\mathcal{X} \times \mathcal{Y} \to [0,1]$. The approximation error of the best verifier in $\mathcal{F}$ is:

\epsilon_{\text{approx}} = \inf_{V \in \mathcal{F}} \sup_{x,y} |V(x,y) - T(x,y)|

Given $n$ i.i.d. training samples $(x_i, y_i, T(x_i, y_i))$, the empirical risk minimizer $\hat{V}$ has estimation error bounded by:

\epsilon_{\text{est}} = \mathbb{E}\left[ \sup_{x,y} |\hat{V}(x,y) - V^*(x,y)| \right]

where $V^*$ is the best approximator in $\mathcal{F}$.

Assumption 7.1.1 (Bounded Error). The total verifier error is bounded: $\sup_{x,y} |\hat{V}(x,y) - T(x,y)| \leq \epsilon_{\max} < \tau$.

7.2 Robust Forward Invariance

Theorem 7.2.1 (Robust Forward Invariance). Under Assumption 7.1.1, if the CBF filter enforces $V(s_k) \geq \tau$ using the approximate verifier $\hat{V}$, then the true truthfulness satisfies:

T(s_k) \geq \tau - \epsilon_{\max} \quad \forall k

Proof. By CBF invariance, $\hat{V}(s_k) \geq \tau$. Then $T(s_k) = \hat{V}(s_k) + (T(s_k) - \hat{V}(s_k)) \geq \tau - |T(s_k) - \hat{V}(s_k)| \geq \tau - \epsilon_{\max}$. $\square$

Corollary 7.2.1 (Safety Margin). To guarantee $T(s_k) \geq \tau_{\text{target}}$, one can set the CBF threshold to $\tau = \tau_{\text{target}} + \epsilon_{\max}$. Then $T(s_k) \geq \tau_{\text{target}} + \epsilon_{\max} - \epsilon_{\max} = \tau_{\text{target}}$.

7.3 Sample Complexity of Verifier Learning

We provide a PAC-style bound for the verifier error.

Theorem 7.3.1 (PAC Bound for Verifier Learning). Let $\mathcal{F}$ have VC dimension $d$. For any $\delta > 0$, with probability at least $1-\delta$ over the draw of $n$ i.i.d. samples, the empirical risk minimizer $\hat{V}$ satisfies:

\mathbb{E}_{x,y}[|\hat{V}(x,y) - T(x,y)|] \leq \inf_{V \in \mathcal{F}} \mathbb{E}[|V - T|] + \mathcal{O}\left( \sqrt{\frac{d \log(n/d) + \log(1/\delta)}{n}} \right)

Proof. Standard VC-theory bound for absolute loss regression. See Vidyasagar (2002), A Theory of Learning and Generalization. $\square$

Remark 7.3.1. For the uniform error bound $\epsilon_{\max}$, one can use the fact that with a Lipschitz verifier class, the generalization error can be controlled uniformly over a covering of the space. Bounds of the form $\epsilon_{\max} = \mathcal{O}(n^{-1/(d+2)})$ are typical.

7.4 Adaptive Threshold Adjustment

If $\epsilon_{\max}$ is unknown, the filter can adapt $\tau$ online based on confidence estimates.

Definition 7.4.1 (Confidence-Aware Barrier). Suppose the verifier provides a confidence interval $[L(s), U(s)]$ for $T(s)$. Define the robust barrier:

h_{\text{robust}}(s) = L(s) - \tau

Then $h_{\text{robust}}(s) \geq 0$ implies $T(s) \geq \tau$ with high probability.

