Chapter 10: Conclusion

This thesis has presented a mathematically rigorous framework for enforcing truthfulness as a hard constraint in language model alignment. By formalizing the problem as a constrained optimization over policy space and applying Lagrangian duality, we derived a primal-dual DPO algorithm with provable convergence rates and explicit bounds on suboptimality and constraint violation. At inference time, we modeled autoregressive generation as a discrete dynamical system and constructed a Control Barrier Function safety filter that guarantees forward invariance of a truth-safe set. The integration of constrained optimization and discrete control theory yields end-to-end guarantees on factual reliability, robustness to verifier error, and compositional safety.

The key theoretical contributions include:

1. A complete formalization of truth-constrained alignment as a saddle-point problem with strong duality under Slater's condition.
2. A Lagrangian DPO loss that eliminates the partition function and enables efficient primal-dual training.
3. A discrete-time CBF framework for token-level safety filtering with proven forward invariance and minimal intervention properties.
4. Robustness guarantees showing that bounded verifier error translates to bounded truthfulness degradation.
5. Compositional theory for multi-constraint safety filters.

All results are established through rigorous definitions, theorems, and proofs. The framework provides a foundational theoretical architecture for reliable language generation, elevating truth from a heuristic objective to a provably invariant system property.

Future work will address the limitations identified in Chapter 9, including non-convex convergence analysis, efficient safety filtering for large vocabularies, and adaptive barrier mechanisms. Empirical validation of the theoretical guarantees in realistic language model deployments remains an important direction for subsequent research.

